{
  "text": "Salmonella requires siderophore synthesis in mice. Bacteria overproduce siderophores in strain backgrounds lacking siderophore import genes such as iroN and fepA [CITATION_1] . Excessive siderophore production could result in local iron starvation and thus poor tissue colonization in vivo. To determine whether the in vivo growth defects observed for the \u232ciroN and \u232cfepA strains reflected enhanced siderophore production, a strain unable to import or produce enterobactin and salmochelin (\u232ciroN \u232cfepA \u232centC) was generated. Mice orogastrically inoculated with individual wildtype or \u232ciroN \u232cfepA \u232centC bacteria were sacrificed at 2 weeks postinfection, and tissue colonization was determined (Fig. 6) .",
